# =============================================================================
# X-TV Environment Variables (Sprint 0)
# =============================================================================
# COPY THIS FILE:
#   cp .env.example .env.local     (or .env)
#
# NEVER COMMIT REAL SECRETS.
# The only file that should ever contain live keys is .env.local (gitignored).
#
# =============================================================================
# SUPABASE (you already have the project)
# =============================================================================
# Get these from: Supabase Dashboard → Project Settings → API
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=https://YOUR-PROJECT.supabase.co
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...

# SERVICE ROLE KEY (server only — never put in client code or .env exposed to browser)
# Used exclusively for the login sync upsert into the users table.
SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...

# =============================================================================
# X OAUTH (next-auth v5 + Twitter provider)
# =============================================================================
# YOU MUST HAVE AN X DEVELOPER APP (Basic tier is enough for S0).
#
# === NOVICE / CLEAR STEPS (exactly what the user asked for) ===
# 1. Go to https://developer.x.com/en/portal/dashboard
# 2. Create / select your App (or "X-TV" / "Visual-x" project).
# 3. In the App → "Keys and tokens" or "User authentication settings":
#      - Enable OAuth 2.0
#      - Set the callback / redirect URL to EXACTLY:
#          http://localhost:3000/api/auth/callback/twitter
#        (Add a second one later for your Vercel production URL, e.g.
#         https://your-x-tv.vercel.app/api/auth/callback/twitter )
#      - Scopes to request: tweet.read  users.read  offline.access
# 4. Copy:
#      - Client ID     → AUTH_TWITTER_ID
#      - Client Secret → AUTH_TWITTER_SECRET
# 5. Generate a strong secret for session encryption (run in terminal):
#      node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(32).toString('base64'))"
#      or: openssl rand -base64 32
#      Paste the result as AUTH_SECRET below.
#
# After filling, restart your dev server (pnpm dev).
#
# Test account mentioned in the original plan: @Mandingo_Fever (use it to verify the full flow).
#
# If you get a redirect_uri mismatch error, double-check the callback URL in the X portal
# matches http://localhost:3000/api/auth/callback/twitter EXACTLY (no trailing slash).
# =============================================================================
AUTH_SECRET=your-super-long-random-base64-string-here
AUTH_TWITTER_ID=your-x-app-client-id
AUTH_TWITTER_SECRET=your-x-app-client-secret

# =============================================================================
# OPTIONAL / FUTURE (Sprint 1+)
# =============================================================================
# X API bearer token (for server-side searches when we stop using only the user context)
# TWITTER_BEARER_TOKEN=

# Upstash Redis or other queue/cache URLs (Sprint 1+)
# UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL=
# UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN=

# Sentry / analytics (Sprint 5+)
# SENTRY_DSN=
# NEXT_PUBLIC_POSTHOG_KEY=

# =============================================================================
# HOW TO USE LOCALLY (Turborepo / monorepo specific)
# =============================================================================
# IMPORTANT: Because we develop with `pnpm --filter=web dev`, Next.js loads
# environment variables from the **web app directory**, not the monorepo root.
#
# Steps:
# 1. Copy this file into the web app:
#    cp .env.example apps/web/.env.local
#
# 2. Fill the required values in `apps/web/.env.local`:
#    - NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL
#    - NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY
#    - SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY
#    - AUTH_SECRET (generate with: node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(32).toString('base64'))" )
#    - AUTH_TWITTER_ID
#    - AUTH_TWITTER_SECRET
#
# 3. Apply the schema: supabase/schema.sql in your Supabase SQL Editor.
#
# 4. Start the app:
#    pnpm --filter=web dev
#
# 5. Visit http://localhost:3000, click "Sign in with X".
#
# After successful login you should land on /tv and a user row should appear
# in your Supabase users table.
#
# The root .env.example is kept for reference / other packages. The web app
# specifically needs its own .env.local inside apps/web/.
